abstract: LISBON, Feb. 29. -- King Manuel to-day issued a decree fixing March 5 as the date of the next general election and another convoking the regular Cortes on April 29. abstract: AUBURN, N.Y., Feb. 29. -- Frank Gillette and his wife. Louise M. Gillette, parents of Chester E. abstract: NEW HAVEN, Conn., Feb. 29. -- Yale's track athletic campaign for this season is being run with the understanding that at the close of the intercollegiate season there will be a trip to England and a four-cornered meet with the English universities after the Olympic games are held. abstract: PARIS, Feb. 20. -- There was barely suppressed elation among the younger and more progressive artists and amateurs of Paris this week when something of a revolution was announced in the management of the historic Gobelins tapestry manufactory. abstract: The new Circle Theatre, at Broadway and Sixtieth Street, was well filled last night for the first of the series of "Nights in Bohemia," which are to be held every Sunday through the rest of the theatrical season. abstract: WASHINGTON, March 3. -- The United States has declared open war on Anarchists. abstract: The most important thing about the agreement reached between King LEOPOLD of Belgium and the Ministry is that it should have been reached at all. When it is carried into effect the Congo territory will pass from the arbitrary control of the King, as a private proprietor, to the responsible control of the Government of Belgium, with the rights and obligations growing out of the international conventions relating to the territory.

abstract: LONDON, Feb. 25. -- Mr. Jacob Popp of High Wycombe is a modern "village Hampden." abstract: CHEYENNE, Wyo., March 8. -- With a cavalcade of cowboys riding at full gallop ahead, swinging their lariats and yelling like Comanche Indians, the Thomas car came into this city shortly after 1 o'clock this afternoon. Practically the whole populace of Cheyenne was out to greet the racers, and the travel stained men and machine got a welcome that was the warmest they had had since leaving "good old Broadway."

abstract: Eighty-eight times in a hundred the daily predictions of the Weather Bureau are correct. That is a small percentage of error, and as Prof. WILLIS L. abstract: ATLANTA, Ga., March 9. -- Manager Griffith put the New York Americans through two courses of hard practice today, devoting all his time and attention to the men, who, it is now practically decided, will make up the regular team for the season. Conroy will play third base, Niles second, Hemphill centre, and Stahl will take care of left field. Chase, Elberfeld, Keeler, and Kleinow will be in their last year's positions.

abstract: WILLIAMSTOWN, Mass., March 9. -- Williams College won the New England Intercollegiate Basket Ball League championship this evening by defeating Wesleyan by 26 to 24. abstract: CLINTON, Iowa, March 10. -- The Protos car, in charge of Lieut. Koeppen of the General Staff of the German Army, left here this morning, heading for Cedar Rapids, expecting to make the eighty-mile run in spite of the heavy roads before nightfall. The car was in splendid condition when it set out, and Lieut. Koeppen was confident of attaining a better place in the race within the next few days.

abstract: The study of all art, plastic, graphic, musical, and literary, is supposed to cultivate good taste. In a broad sense, it infrequently does so. Notoriously, competent musicians dress in bad taste and have vague ideas of form and color. Famous painters are often fond of bad literature. On the other hand, people conspicuous for good taste often have studied no art, and like the young ladies in MOLIERE'S play comprehend things without learning them.

abstract: HAMMONDSPORT, N.Y., March 12. -- Prof. Alexander Graham Bell's new aerodrome, the "Red Wing," had its test flight over Lake Keuka to-day. abstract: Fire Commissioner Hugh Bonner, who had been ill of pneumonia for the last two days at his home, 636 West End Avenue, died at 12:30 o'clock this morning. His illness took a turn for the worse in the night. Commissioner Bonner contracted a cold a week ago, but persisted in attending to his duties at his office daily despite the advice of his physician. On Monday he was compelled to take to his bed.

abstract: The Musical Art Society completed its fifteenth season with its second concert last evening in Carnegie Hall before a large audience. Its programme contained a number of works that the society has sung before, but all of them of an importance that warranted their repetition. In one case, that of Palestrina's "Stabat Mater" for double chorus, it was the fifth performance that the society has given.

abstract: In THE SATURDAY REVIEW OF BOOKS of Feb. 29 there was an editorial which referred to the saying, "Exceptions prove the rule." abstract: LONDON, March 14. -- I hear on good authority that Lieut. Gen. Sir Arthur Paget will succeed Lord Methuen in command of the army corps, with headquarters at Colchester. abstract: Judge Holt of the United States District Court yesterday appointed Robert C. Morris receiver of the Breakwater Construction and Engineering Company of 115 Broadway, which is said to have $2,000,000 worth of contracts on hand for Government work. abstract: When Leopold Gusthal died on Friday at his home, 1,185 Lexington Avenue, an interesting and useful career ended. For sixty years Mr. Gusthal had lived in New York, and as he prospered expended his income in charitable enterprises rather than in the pursuit of luxuries. Mr. Gusthal was in his eighty-second year. He leaves two sisters, Mrs. Babette Kohn and Miss Bertha Gusthal.

abstract: Mr. JOHN BIGELOW in his teens fished in a pure Hudson. Its waters are no longer pure. They "swarmed with white bass, dickups, eels, shad, and herring," he says, which have departed, but not because they were "fished out." In his address to the Mayor, reported yesterday, Mr. BIGELOW requested that the Hudson-Fulton Celebration Commission include in its plan and scope the river's repurification.

abstract: Cross-country runners are busy preparing for the senior metropolitan A.A.U. championship at Celtic Park, April 5. abstract: The total of foreign trade for February is as remarkable as the indications from the outgo of domestic products. Imports shrunk from $123,000,000 to $79,124,401, as compared with February, 1907, and exports increased from $159,517,221 to $167,867,762. The result is that the excess of exports was $88,743,361, or an increased excess of exports of $52,000,000, against a total excess of exports of $36,511,538 last year.

abstract: CHICAGO, March 16. -- C.F. Conklin of Chicago won the second game in the National amateur 14.2 billiard tournament to-day, defeating E.W. Gardner of Passaic, N.J., by the score of 400 to 271. Conklin's average was 12 28-31 and Gardner's 8 23-31. Conklin took the lead in his initial inning, when he made a run of 141, and was never overtaken by Gardner.

abstract: BOSTON, Mass., March 16. -- The Atlantic Baseball Association was formally organized in this city to-day. At a meeting held in the office of the American League the circuit was decided upon as follows: Lewiston, Me.; Portland, Me.; Newport, R.I.; Pawtucket, R.I.; Woonsocket, R.I., and Taunton, Mass. It was voted to open the season May 2 and end it Sept. 7.

abstract: PARIS, March 16. -- The situation between the Haitian Government and France has become acute and critical. The French Legation at Port-au-prince is menaced, and a general massacre of the white residents of the island is feared. This information was conveyed in an official dispatch to the Foreign Office from M. Carteron, the French Minister to Haiti.

abstract: ALBANY, March 17. -- Gov. Hughes's anti-race track gambling legislation suffered another setback to-day which will result in more delay. Senator Agnew called up his bill with a view of having it made a special order for to-morrow. Senator Grady, minority leader, interposed an objection, which under the rules was sufficient to block the move of Senator Agnew.

abstract: WASHINGTON, March 17. -- More than 150 students in the Georgetown University to-day celebrated St. Patrick's Day by engaging in a riot, nearly drowning one of the Jesuit fathers with a stream from a fire hose, smashing crockery, and marching from the university in a body. To-night twenty were expelled when they returned from a day in the city, and 130 have been suspended.

abstract: COBRE, Nevada, March 17. -- After running through several sandstorms the Thomas car, leader in the Paris Matin-NEW YORK TIMES race from New York to Paris, arrived in this town, 182 miles from Ogden, at 9 o'clock to-night. abstract: The funeral of Fire Commissioner Hugh Bonnet was held yesterday morning from his home, 636 West End Avenue, whence the body was taken to the Roman Catholic Church of the Holy Name, Ninety-sixth Street and Amsterdam Avenue, where services were held. abstract: A short-circuit of the electric cables stopped the entire elevated system in Manhattan yesterday afternoon. The stoppage came at 1:58 o'clock. The cables affected were those running between the Seventy-fourth Street generating plant and Sub-Station 5 on Division Street. abstract: While at anchor in the bay in the dense fog of the early morning yesterday the big North German Lloyd liner Kronprinz Wilhelm, with 892 passengers on board, was rammed by the British freighter Crown of Castile. The liner was caught by the blunt bow of the freighter squarely in the stern, and when the vessels separated the German ship had a fifteen-foot hole in her overhang, but fortunately far above the water line.

abstract: HARTFORD, Conn., March 18. -- That Isabella Beecher Hooker, sister of Henry Ward Beecher, was influenced by her belief in spiritualism to cut off her granddaughter in her will, was declared in the Superior Court to-day. abstract: LAKEWOOD, N.J., March 18. -- Ex-President Grover Cleveland passed his seventy-first birthday in Lakewood quietly to-day. He received a large number of congratulatory telegrams and flowers from his friends, and Manager Berry of the Lakewood Hotel, where Mr. Cleveland is stopping, gave an elaborate luncheon as a surprise for the distinguished guest in a private room elaborately decorated with roses and carnations and draped with American flags.

abstract: WASHINGTON, March 19. -- In memorials presented to-day to Vice President Fairbanks and Speaker Cannon organized labor formally served notice on Congress that it expected certain favoring legislation at this session. Four measures are especially desired. If these are not enacted there is to be trouble, for in veiled but unmistakable language labor announced its intention of then entering the National campaign to attain its ends.

abstract: BERLIN, March 19. -- The Government to-night publishes a cablegram from South Africa reporting a battle between a German expeditionary force and a body of Hottentots in the Kalarari Desert. abstract: The details of a new alleged swindle along the lines of the famous "Fads and Fancies" scheme of two years ago, in which many wealthy persons gave up large sums, were divulged at Police Headquarters last night by Detective McConville. abstract: EVANSTON, Wyoming, March 20. -- After spending more than forty hours in deep mud three miles west of Granger. abstract: The American divorce case in Paris was caused directly by a weak "no trump" make in a game of bridge. We have been fearing that scandal and ruin would come sooner or later from one of those overrated declarations of "no trumps" to the score. In this case a man and his wife were partners, and the lady, having dealt the cards, declared "no trumps."

abstract: ALBANY, March 20. -- Attorney General Jackson sent a letter to the Senate to-day asking for an investigation by that body of his acts, declaring that public confidence in his office had been shaken by attacks upon his administration. abstract: The McClure Company announces for publication on March 25 three books of interest. The first is "Love's Logic," by Anthony Hope, a volume containing fifteen of this widely popular writer's new short stories. They deal with different phases of love, that really most illogical of human passions, and picture the life among the upper and aristocratic classes of England, often penetrating even further, into the homes and hearts of royalty.

abstract: WASHINGTON, March 20. -- The census report issued to-day shows that the cotton crop grown in 1907 aggregated 11,261,163 running bales, counting round bales as half bales and including linters, and showed a total of 27,577 active ginneries for 1907. abstract: Yale's freshmen fencers defeated the trio of Columbia yesterday afternoon in a meet held in Earl Hall, on Morningside Heights, by a score of 6 bouts to 3. This is the first time that Yale and Columbia freshmen have ever met in fencing, and the first time in four years that the Columbia freshmen have contested with teams from other universities.

abstract: OGDEN, March 21. -- After a long journey through the mountains, over bad roads, the Italian Zust car reached this city at 4 o'clock this afternoon. It will be overhauled here to-night, and will leave early in the morning on a hard chase of the Thomas car. The Italians still have some hope of reaching San Francisco in the van.

abstract: WACO, Texas, March 21. -- McGraw's third team defeated the local Texas league team today, 8 to 5. The weather was very cold, and Matthewson, who pitched the full game for New York, did not extend himself. The Giant's line-up was composed mostly of pitchers, and their fielding was bad. Terry McGovern played right field for the visitors.

abstract: SILVER CITY, N.M., March 21. -- The Republican Territorial Convention to-day adopted resolutions indorsing Secretary of War Taft for President and instructing the New Mexico delegates to Chicago to vote for him. abstract: BALTIMORE, Md., March 21. -- An audience that largely made up in enthusiasm what it lacked in numbers to-night say George Hackenschmidt, the Russian wrestler, fail in his undertaking to throw Gus Schoenlein of this city in fifteen minutes. abstract: OGDEN, Utah, March 22. -- The Italian Zust car pulled out of Ogden to-day at 12 o'clock and made a run to Kelton, Utah, 80 miles from Ogden. It arrived there late in the evening and remained for the night. The road between Ogden and Kelton was in good condition. The car will start early in the morning for the Nevada line, and the Italians expect to make a fast run across the "Sagebrush" State.

abstract: Hunt's Point Park, in the Bronx, is an undeveloped stretch of ninety-seven lots of marsh land, about two-thirds of which are under water. The Assessors of the City of New York in 1906 assessed it as worth $4,300. The city bought it within a year and paid $252,118 for it. These facts were brought out yesterday at the inquiry being held by the Commissioners of Accounts into the affairs of Borough President Haffen's office.

abstract: RAWLINS, Wyo., March 24. -- After another days run through a driving storm, the German Protos car stopped here at 6:35 o'clock this evening, seventy-eight miles nearer the end of its transcontinental run in the New York to Paris race. abstract: BOSTON, March 24. -- In an address before the Economic Club to-night Stuyvesant Fish, formerly President of the Illinois Central Railroad, discussed the railroad problem. abstract: ITHACA, N.Y., March 24. -- Coach Coogan to-day made the final selection of the Cornell baseball squad, which will leave Thursday for the annual Southern trip, opening with a game at Annapolis on Saturday. The team will be: Pitchers, Gable, Caldwell. Goodwillle, and Barker; catchers, Lally and Williams; first base, Watton; second base. abstract: MADRID, March 24. -- The arrest in Paris of Henri Rochette on charges of swindling, has created stupefaction in many parts of Spain. abstract: BERLIN, March 24. -- Speaking in the Reichstag to-day Chancellor Von Buelow said the efforts of the great powers to extinguish the conflagration in Macedonia had been rendered futile because fresh fuel was constantly being thrown on the fire from the outside. The foundation of the trouble did not lie in strife between Christendom and Mohammedanism, but in the bitter struggle between the various Christian nationalities in the Balkans.

abstract: ROME, March 24. -- King Victor Emmanuel left for Venice this evening, where he will meet the German Emperor, who left Berlin to-day and is now on his way to that city, prior to going on board the imperial yacht, which will take him to Corfu. abstract: TUXEDO, March 24. -- Amos T. French spent a part of to-day at Tucks Eden, his beautiful home here leaving for New York this afternoon. abstract: " Marta of the Lowlands" is a play of primitive emotions. In its colorful fabric it blends a story of ruthless passion, cruelty, and violence, of sin committed under pressure, of tardy expiation, and of eventual purification through suffering. In these respects it is like innumerable plays that come and go in the recurring seasons, but it has appeared at times as something with a deeper and firmer root.

abstract: The class sewing for the Fresh Air Fund of the Cathedral of St. John the Divine held its last meeting of the season yesterday morning at the residence of Mrs. J. Borden Harriman. abstract: Superficially, at least, there was plenty of optimism in the speculative market yesterday. In the afternoon, when Union Pacific advanced sharply beyond 128, there was even evidence of enthusiasm among the professionals. abstract: LONDON, March 24. -- The news of the death of the Duke of Devonshire at Cannes came unexpectedly to England and has caused widespread regret. He had been ailing since he suffered a sudden attack of heart weakness at Windsor Castle last June. Alarming reports reached London during his sojourn in Egypt this Winter, but recent accounts of his health had been reassuring.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, March 25. -- Prince Helie de Sagan, the prisoner of the Bellevue-Stratford, concluded his self-imposed confinement this morning and escaped from the city. He had been there since Monday morning, and, so far as can be determined, he did not leave the hotel for any sight-seeing or business expeditions, although the only circumstance to prevent this was the presence of several persons who wanted to know just what he was most anxious to conceal.

abstract: MEXICO CITY, March 26. -- Mexico City experienced two severe earthquake shocks to-day. The first shock came at 4:30 o'clock this evening and lasted 4 minutes and 28 seconds. The shock was similar to that felt in this city about a year ago, the oscillations being of a long, swaying variety.

abstract: TOLEDO, O., March 28. -- The Ohio Circuit Court to-day affirmed the decision of the lower court in the cases of the twenty prominent lumbermen of Toledo who last July were sentenced to the workhouse for six months under the Valentine Anti-Trust law. abstract: Excavations will soon be completed for the eighteen-story addition to the Masonic Temple, to be erected at a cost of $1,000,000 at 46 to 54 West Twenty-fourth Street. abstract: A splendid set of games was run off night in the Seventh Regiment Armory, the events being the fifty-third games held under the auspices of the Seventh Regiment Athletic Association. abstract: ANNAPOLIS, Md., March 28. -- Cornell lost a fine contest to the Naval Academy this afternoon by the score of 4 to 3. Cornell played an errorless game and out-batted the local nine, but Barker's wildness and the bunching of hits by the Navy enabled the Navy lads to win. Barker, the Cornell pitcher, gave three bases on balls in the first inning, which with Stiles's single gave the Navy a lead of two runs.

abstract: Mme. abstract: George Milne has sold to the Standard Oil Company of New York, for the J.B. Cornell Company, the seven-story building, 75 by 100, at 551- to 555 West Twenty-fifth Street. After extensive alterations the building will be used by the Standard Oil Company as offices and warerooms for one of its branch departments.
